05213nam a22008535i 9780812208405DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20132013pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979910471  a97808122084057 a10.9783/97808122084052doi  a(DE-B1597)449762  a(OCoLC)859162344  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aLIT0041902bisacsh04a880.9/0022231 aKaldellis, Anthony, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEthnography After Antiquity :bForeign Lands and Peoples in Byzantine Literature /cAnthony Kaldellis. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEmpire and After00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tChapter 1. Ethnography in Late Antique Historiography -- tChapter 2. Byzantine Information- Gathering Behind the Veil of Silence -- tChapter 3. Explaining the Relative Decline of Ethnography in the Middle Period -- tChapter 4. The Genres and Politics of Middle Byzantine Ethnography -- tChapter 5. Ethnography in Palaiologan Literature -- tEpilogue: Looking to a New World -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlthough Greek and Roman authors wrote ethnographic texts describing foreign cultures, ethnography seems to disappear from Byzantine literature after the seventh century C.E.—a perplexing exception for a culture so strongly self-identified with the Roman empire. Yet the Byzantines, geographically located at the heart of the upheavals that led from the ancient to the modern world, had abundant and sophisticated knowledge of the cultures with which they struggled and bargained. Ethnography After Antiquity examines both the instances and omissions of Byzantine ethnography, exploring the political and religious motivations for writing (or not writing) about other peoples.Through the ethnographies embedded in classical histories, military manuals, Constantine VII's De administrando imperio, and religious literature, Anthony Kaldellis shows Byzantine authors using accounts of foreign cultures as vehicles to critique their own state or to demonstrate Romano-Christian superiority over Islam. He comes to the startling conclusion that the Byzantines did not view cultural differences through a purely theological prism: their Roman identity, rather than their orthodoxy, was the vital distinction from cultures they considered heretic and barbarian. Filling in the previously unexplained gap between antiquity and the resurgence of ethnography in the late Byzantine period, Ethnography After Antiquity offers new perspective on how Byzantium positioned itself with and against the dramatically shifting world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aByzantine literaturexThemes, motives. 0aCultural awarenesszByzantine Empire. 0aEthnic attitudes in literature. 0aEthnic attitudeszByzantine Empire. 4aLiterature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aAncient Studies.  aAnthropology.  aClassics.  aCultural Studies.  aFolklore.  aHistory.  aLinguistics.  aLiterature.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook-Package Literaturez978311041354008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311045954840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081220840540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812208405423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812208405.jpg  a978-3-11-041345-8  Penn Press eBook Package Complete Colle